  >
    There are five characteristics of a hypergeometric experiment.
    
      1. You take samples from  *two* groups.
      2. You are concerned with a group of interest, called the first group.
      3. You sample  *without replacement* from the combined groups. For example, you want to choose a softball team from a combined group of 11 men and 13 women. The team consists of ten players.
      4. Each pick is  *not* independent, since sampling is without replacement. In the softball example, the probability of picking a woman first is <math xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:cnxorg="http://cnx.rice.edu/system-info" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"> <mrow>  <mfrac>   <mrow>    <mn>13</mn>   </mrow>   <mrow>    <mn>24</mn>   </mrow>  </mfrac> </mrow></math>. The probability of picking a man second is <math xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:cnxorg="http://cnx.rice.edu/system-info" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"> <mrow>  <mfrac>   <mn>11</mn>   <mrow>    <mn>23</mn>   </mrow>  </mfrac> </mrow></math> if a woman was picked first. It is <math xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:cnxorg="http://cnx.rice.edu/system-info" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"> <mrow>  <mfrac>   <mn>10</mn>   <mrow>    <mn>23</mn>   </mrow>  </mfrac> </mrow></math> if a man was picked first. The probability of the second pick depends on what happened in the first pick.
      5. You are  *not* dealing with Bernoulli Trials.
    
    The outcomes of a hypergeometric experiment fit a  **hypergeometric probability** distribution. The random variable  *X* = the number of items from the group of interest.

